==English==

===Etymology===
The saying comes from the 1866 [[w:Dion Boucicault|Dion Boucicault]] play, ''Flying Scud'', in which a character knowingly breezes past a difficult situation saying, "Excuse me Mr. Quail, I can't stop; I've got to see a man about a dog."

===Verb===
{{head|en|verb|head=[[see]] a [[man]] about a [[horse]]}}

# {{label|en|slang|idiomatic|euphemistic}} ''Used in place of a real explanation when excusing oneself for a short period of time, particularly to use a toilet.''
#: ''I'll be back in [[two shakes of a lamb's tail]]. I've just got to visit the [[ladies' room]] to '''see a man about a horse'''.''

